Our members work to advance the rights of refugees, asylum seekers, stateless

833
01:01:38.106 --> 01:01:41.066
people, internally displaced people, and other people on the move.

834
01:01:42.446 --> 01:01:45.466
I also speak today from my own lived experience.

835
01:01:45.766 --> 01:01:48.146
I am a former Rohingya refugee from Myanmar.

836
01:01:49.006 --> 01:01:52.866
I came to New Zealand in 2019 and became a New Zealand citizen only

837
01:01:52.886 --> 01:01:53.306
last year.

838
01:01:54.286 --> 01:01:58.086
So I speak not only from a regional advocacy perspective, but also as

839
01:01:58.166 --> 01:02:01.706
someone who understand personally what it means to seek

840
01:02:01.786 --> 01:02:05.046
safety and rebuild life in a new country.

841
01:02:06.386 --> 01:02:10.326
I want to begin by acknowledging New Zealand's longstanding role in refugee

842
01:02:10.386 --> 01:02:13.626
protection and resettlement. New Zealand has provided safety

843
01:02:14.326 --> 01:02:17.025
and a new beginning to many people from our region.

844
01:02:17.706 --> 01:02:20.306
Its Refugee Quota Program, Community Sponsorship

845
01:02:20.926 --> 01:02:23.826
Initiative, and humanitarian commitments have made

846
01:02:25.006 --> 01:02:27.106
a real difference in many people lives.

847
01:02:27.626 --> 01:02:30.686
That is why APRRN is deeply concerned about the Immigration

848
01:02:32.686 --> 01:02:35.466
Bill and the related parliamentary paper.

849
01:02:36.466 --> 01:02:37.746
Our central message is simple.

850
01:02:38.626 --> 01:02:41.906
APRRN urges the committee to recommend that this amendment

851
01:02:42.526 --> 01:02:46.326
be withdrawn or, at the very least, substantially reconsidered.

852
01:02:46.826 --> 01:02:50.496
We are concerned that the proposed changes risk undermining New Zealand's

853
01:02:50.546 --> 01:02:54.086
reputation for fairness, human rights, and refugee protection.

854
01:02:55.506 --> 01:02:59.286
They may also have serious consequences for refugees, asylum seekers,

855
01:02:59.506 --> 01:03:03.426
migrants, children, women, and other people who are already in

856
01:03:03.466 --> 01:03:04.766
vulnerable situations.

857
01:03:05.726 --> 01:03:09.206
So I would like to focus on three main concerns and then briefly address

858
01:03:09.286 --> 01:03:13.266
any wider impacts. The first concern, APRRN is

859
01:03:13.306 --> 01:03:16.986
concerned that the proposed power for immigration officers to request

860
01:03:17.046 --> 01:03:18.726
identification based on suspicion,

861
01:03:19.846 --> 01:03:23.266
even if the intention is administrative, this power

862
01:03:23.746 --> 01:03:25.946
may have discriminatory impacts in practice.

863
01:03:27.166 --> 01:03:28.666
People who are visibly migrants

864
01:03:29.526 --> 01:03:33.086
and from refugee background, Muslim, Asian, African,

865
01:03:33.326 --> 01:03:37.266
Middle Eastern, or from the racialized communities may feel they are being

866
01:03:37.286 --> 01:03:40.226
treated as a suspicion because of how they look,

867
01:03:41.126 --> 01:03:45.006
how they speak, their accents, their name, ethnicity, or country of

868
01:03:45.046 --> 01:03:45.525
origin.

869
01:03:46.466 --> 01:03:50.286
For refugees and asylum seekers, this can particularly be harmful.

870
01:03:51.326 --> 01:03:54.996
Many have already experienced state surveillance, arbitrary

871
01:03:55.026 --> 01:03:58.886
questioning, police harassment, or threats from authorities in

872
01:03:58.926 --> 01:04:02.706
their countries of origin. When similar dynamic appear in a

873
01:04:02.746 --> 01:04:05.926
country of supposed protection, it can trigger fear,

874
01:04:06.586 --> 01:04:08.146
trauma, and mistrust.

875
01:04:10.306 --> 01:04:13.886
The practical effect may be that people avoid public institution.

876
01:04:13.926 --> 01:04:17.446
They may avoid hospital, police, schools, employment

877
01:04:17.546 --> 01:04:21.086
services or family violence support because they fear immigration

878
01:04:21.126 --> 01:04:22.606
consequences if they do so.

879
01:04:23.826 --> 01:04:26.966
This does not make communities safer.

880
01:04:27.046 --> 01:04:29.806
It pushes people further into the shadows.

881
01:04:30.666 --> 01:04:34.526
Secondly, APRRN is deeply concerned about the proposed restriction on

882
01:04:34.586 --> 01:04:38.406
alternative visa pathways for people who withdraw asylum

883
01:04:38.526 --> 01:04:41.766
claims. This one is the most troubling parts of the proposal.

884
01:04:43.006 --> 01:04:45.986
People may withdraw asylum claims for many legitimate reasons.

885
01:04:46.606 --> 01:04:48.166
Their circumstances may change.

886
01:04:49.046 --> 01:04:52.886
They may enter a genuine relationship with New Zealand partner.

887
01:04:53.526 --> 01:04:57.146
They may marry. They may have children. They may receive a job offer.

888
01:04:58.026 --> 01:05:01.806
They may become eligible for another visa pathway that

889
01:05:01.966 --> 01:05:04.086
better reflects their current situation.

890
01:05:04.706 --> 01:05:08.186
A rigid ban on alternative visa pathway risks punishing people

891
01:05:08.886 --> 01:05:11.026
for ordinary legitimate life change.

892
01:05:12.166 --> 01:05:15.766
For example, if a person seeking asylum forms a

893
01:05:15.846 --> 01:05:19.796
genuine and settled relationship, it seems unnecessarily harsh to prevent them from

894
01:05:19.846 --> 01:05:23.096
applying for a partnership visa simply because they

895
01:05:23.206 --> 01:05:24.386
previously sought asylum.

896
01:05:25.726 --> 01:05:29.286
Similarly, if someone has skill, employment, and opportunity to contribute to New

897
01:05:29.346 --> 01:05:33.206
Zealand, the law should not automatically block that person from

898
01:05:33.406 --> 01:05:35.006
regularizing their status.

899
01:05:35.846 --> 01:05:39.186
Thirdly, APRRN is concerned about the proposed limitation on humanitarian appeal

900
01:05:39.246 --> 01:05:42.446
rights. Humanitarian appeal rights are not a loophole.

901
01:05:42.526 --> 01:05:46.286
They are important safe ground. They allow independent oversight in

902
01:05:46.346 --> 01:05:49.766
complex cases where removal of New Zealand may have serious

903
01:05:49.806 --> 01:05:50.526
consequences.

904
01:05:51.466 --> 01:05:55.226
This safeguard is especially important for people with trauma history,

905
01:05:56.046 --> 01:05:59.726
health concern, family responsibility, or risks of

906
01:05:59.786 --> 01:06:03.706
harms if they return. Limiting appeal rights may

907
01:06:03.766 --> 01:06:05.426
have serious consequences for children.

908
01:06:05.926 --> 01:06:09.506
Many families facing deportation have children who have grown up here,

909
01:06:10.266 --> 01:06:13.866
attend school here, speak English, have friends here,

910
01:06:14.766 --> 01:06:18.546
and may have very limited connection to their parents' country of origin.

911
01:06:19.086 --> 01:06:22.566
Deportation can disrupt education, damage mental health,

912
01:06:22.886 --> 01:06:26.766
separate families, send children to unfamiliar environments where

913
01:06:26.806 --> 01:06:29.546
they may not speak the language or have support.

914
01:06:30.206 --> 01:06:33.846
New Zealand has obligation under the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child.

915
01:06:35.046 --> 01:06:38.606
Meaningful humanitarian appeal rights help ensure that children's best

916
01:06:38.666 --> 01:06:42.586
interests are properly considered before life-changing decisions are

917
01:06:42.626 --> 01:06:46.466
made. I also want to briefly highlight the wider impacts of this bill.

918
01:06:47.846 --> 01:06:51.706
For refugees, safety is not a physical safety.

919
01:06:51.826 --> 01:06:55.246
Safety also means stability, dignity, belonging,

920
01:06:55.766 --> 01:06:58.826
and the ability to rebuild their life without constant fear.

921
01:06:59.666 --> 01:07:02.976
Many refugees arrive here after years of persecution,

922
01:07:03.226 --> 01:07:07.086
insecurity, displacement, detention, exploitation, or family

923
01:07:07.106 --> 01:07:10.502
separationMeasures that increase

924
01:07:10.542 --> 01:07:14.522
surveillance, reduce appeal rights, or create fear of deportation

925
01:07:14.722 --> 01:07:18.622
can worsen anxiety, depression, trauma responses, and

926
01:07:18.682 --> 01:07:19.352
insecurity.

927
01:07:20.262 --> 01:07:24.232
From my own experience, even with English language skill that I had when

928
01:07:24.342 --> 01:07:28.202
I first came here, work experience, and some understanding of

929
01:07:28.302 --> 01:07:30.822
institution, my first years in New Zealand were not easy.

930
01:07:30.942 --> 01:07:34.762
It took time to understand system, become independent, and feel

931
01:07:34.802 --> 01:07:38.042
grounded. For people facing language barrier,

932
01:07:38.942 --> 01:07:42.882
trauma, family separation, racism, poverty, disability,

933
01:07:42.962 --> 01:07:46.502
and insecure immigration status, the challenges are even greater.

934
01:07:47.742 --> 01:07:51.342
The law should support people to feel safe enough to participate,

935
01:07:51.782 --> 01:07:54.802
contribute, and belong. It should not deepen fear.

936
01:07:55.542 --> 01:07:56.582
We're also concerned

937
01:07:57.702 --> 01:08:00.722
that this bill may contribute to negative public

938
01:08:00.782 --> 01:08:04.452
discourses about refugees and

939
01:08:04.482 --> 01:08:04.982
migrants.

940
01:08:06.142 --> 01:08:09.722
Around the world, refugees and migrants are increasingly used as

941
01:08:09.742 --> 01:08:13.682
political scapegoats. They are blamed for crime, housing

942
01:08:13.782 --> 01:08:17.583
pressure, economy difficulty, public service strain, or

943
01:08:17.663 --> 01:08:21.463
social decline. New Zealand has historically taken a more principled and balanced

944
01:08:21.482 --> 01:08:25.352
approach. Our concern is that the bill may unintentionally shift the

945
01:08:25.382 --> 01:08:29.202
public conversation in a more punitive and

946
01:08:29.262 --> 01:08:30.602
suspicious direction.

947
01:08:31.762 --> 01:08:35.702
That would be harmful not only for refugees and migrants, but for New Zealand

948
01:08:35.742 --> 01:08:39.663
society as a whole. Finally, APRN is particularly concerned

949
01:08:39.722 --> 01:08:43.382
about the impact on women and girls and other groups facing heightened

950
01:08:43.442 --> 01:08:47.123
vulnerability. Women and girls with insecure immigration status

951
01:08:47.822 --> 01:08:51.583
may already face family violence, gender-based violence, sexual exploitation,

952
01:08:51.782 --> 01:08:55.632
trafficking, workplace exploitation, economic dependence, and

953
01:08:55.702 --> 01:08:57.742
language barrier and social isolation.

954
01:08:58.302 --> 01:09:02.112
If immigration settings create more fear of enforcement and

955
01:09:02.163 --> 01:09:05.142
deportation, women may be less likely to seek help.

956
01:09:05.922 --> 01:09:09.202
A woman experiencing violence may decide not to call police,

957
01:09:09.842 --> 01:09:13.822
not to access healthcare, or not to report abuse, and not to approach

958
01:09:13.882 --> 01:09:17.612
a supportive organization because she fears immigration consequences

959
01:09:17.962 --> 01:09:21.682
for herself and for her family. The restriction on alternative

960
01:09:21.702 --> 01:09:24.463
visa pathways may also have gender impact.

961
01:09:24.562 --> 01:09:28.083
Some women may withdraw asylum claims because of family pressure, trauma,

962
01:09:28.642 --> 01:09:32.302
misinformation, dependence on a partner, lack of legal advice, or

963
01:09:32.402 --> 01:09:33.802
relationship changes.

964
01:09:35.062 --> 01:09:38.543
A rigid ban could leave them with fewer options

965
01:09:38.802 --> 01:09:41.623
to regularize or escape unsafe situation.

966
01:09:42.262 --> 01:09:45.663
We therefore ask the committee to assess these reforms through a gender,

967
01:09:46.482 --> 01:09:47.862
child rights, disability,

968
01:09:48.842 --> 01:09:52.163
race equity, refugee protection, and trauma-informed lens.

969
01:09:53.482 --> 01:09:57.422
In conclusion, APRN respectfully urges the committee to reconsider

970
01:09:57.432 --> 01:10:01.302
the proposed amendments. New Zealand should not move away from its profound

971
01:10:01.402 --> 01:10:05.142
tradition of refugee protection, fairness, human rights, and humanitarian

972
01:10:05.182 --> 01:10:08.662
leadership. At a time of rising displacement, shrinking

973
01:10:08.722 --> 01:10:12.582
resettlement places, reduced humanitarian funding, and increasing

974
01:10:12.662 --> 01:10:16.542
anti-migrants rhetoric globally, New Zealand leadership matters

975
01:10:16.582 --> 01:10:17.642
now more than ever.

976
01:10:19.602 --> 01:10:21.102
APRN recommends that the committee

977
01:10:22.102 --> 01:10:25.962
withdraw or sustain consideration for the proposed amendment bill for that matter.

